├── backend/
│   ├── main.py             # FastAPI backend API server
│   ├── requirements.txt    # Python dependencies
│   └── Dockerfile          # Dockerfile for Cloud Run
├── worker/
│   ├── worker.py           # FastAPI worker processing jobs
│   ├── requirements.txt    # Python dependencies
│   └── Dockerfile          # Dockerfile for Cloud Run
└── frontend/
    ├── package.json        # React dependencies and scripts
    ├── public/
    │   └── index.html      # HTML entry point
    └── src/
        ├── index.jsx       # React root render
        └── App.jsx         # React component for demo UI


Prerequisites

GCP Account with the following APIs enabled:

Cloud Run

Cloud Tasks

Cloud Storage

Firestore (Native mode)

Python 3.11+ (backend/worker)

Node.js 18+ (frontend)

Docker for building images

Optional: gcloud CLI for deployment

1️⃣ Setup GCP Resources
Set project
gcloud config set project YOUR_PROJECT_ID

Create Cloud Storage bucket (for export/import files):

gsutil mb -l us-central1 gs://demo-export-bucket

Enable Firestore in Native mode (default location)

Create Cloud Tasks queue:

gcloud tasks queues create export-queue --location=us-central1

Note your GCP Project ID, region, and Cloud Run URLs for backend and worker.

gcloud iam service-accounts create export-sa


2️⃣ Backend Deployment (FastAPI)

Navigate to backend:

cd backend

Build Docker image:

docker build -t export-api .
gcloud auth configure-docker

docker tag export-api gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/export-api
docker push gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/export-api

gcloud run deploy export-api \
  ... \
  --service-account export-sa@YOUR_PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com

gcloud iam service-accounts create export-sa

gcloud projects add-iam-policy-binding YOUR_PROJECT_ID \
  --member="serviceAccount:export-sa@YOUR_PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com" \
  --role="roles/datastore.user"

gcloud projects add-iam-policy-binding YOUR_PROJECT_ID \
  --member="serviceAccount:export-sa@YOUR_PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com" \
  --role="roles/storage.admin"

gcloud projects add-iam-policy-binding YOUR_PROJECT_ID \
  --member="serviceAccount:export-sa@YOUR_PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com" \
  --role="roles/cloudtasks.enqueuer"



Deploy to Cloud Run:

gcloud run deploy export-api \
  --image gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/export-api \
  --platform managed \
  --region us-central1 \
  --allow-unauthenticated

Copy the Cloud Run URL and update WORKER_URL in main.py to point to your worker endpoint.

3️⃣ Worker Deployment (FastAPI)

Navigate to worker:

cd worker

Build Docker image:

docker build -t export-worker .

docker tag export-worker gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/export-worker
docker push gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/export-worker

gcloud run deploy export-worker \
  ... \
  --service-account export-sa@YOUR_PROJECT_ID.iam.gserviceaccount.com

Deploy to Cloud Run:

gcloud run deploy export-worker \
  --image gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT_ID/export-worker \
  --platform managed \
  --region us-central1 \
  --allow-unauthenticated

  
4️⃣ Frontend Deployment (React)

Navigate to frontend:

cd frontend

Install dependencies:

npm install

Build frontend:

npm run build

Serve locally for testing:

npx serve -s build

Replace YOUR_BACKEND_CLOUD_RUN_URL in App.jsx with your backend URL.

Optionally, deploy frontend to Cloud Run or Firebase Hosting.

5️⃣ Usage

Open the frontend in browser.

Click Start Export → backend generates a job ID and enqueues a task.

The frontend polls the backend /api/jobs/{job_id}/status.

Once done, a signed download URL appears → click to download the mock export JSON file.

For import, extend backend and worker to accept file uploads via Cloud Storage.

6️⃣ Load Testing

You can simulate multiple export requests using the provided Python async load test:

python load_test.py

Adjust TOTAL_REQUESTS and CONCURRENT_REQUESTS to test system load.

Monitor Cloud Tasks queue, Cloud Run worker metrics, and Firestore job statuses to ensure proper scaling.

7️⃣ Features

Fully asynchronous export/import using Cloud Tasks and Cloud Run

Handles large payloads without blocking the web server

Uses signed URLs for secure downloads

Supports scalable worker processing

Easy to extend for real-world data

8️⃣ Notes

Check export with load_test.py (before run pip install aiohttp)

